# Production Mindset Transformation

A Senior/Staff-level skill for building systems that fail gracefully, degrade predictably,
and recover automatically. Rooted in failure-first design philosophy.

---

## Core Philosophy

> "Every system will fail. The question is whether you designed the failure."

Four principles underpin everything in this skill:

1. **Failure is a first-class citizen** — Model failure paths before happy paths
2. **Blast radius over prevention** — You cannot prevent all failures; contain them
3. **Observability is not optional** — If you can't see it, you can't fix it in production
4. **Degrade, don't die** — Every dependency must have a fallback answer

---

## Skill Components

### 1. Concept Maps
Connect philosophy → pattern → implementation. Always present as:
- The failure mode (what goes wrong)
- The blast radius (what it affects)
- The mitigation pattern (circuit breaker, timeout budget, backpressure, etc.)
- The Go implementation hook

### 2. Live Code Labs (Go, Production-Grade)

All labs use:
- `context.Context` for cancellation and deadline propagation
- Structured logging (`log/slog` or `zap`)
- Prometheus metrics at every boundary
- Realistic load simulation (not toy examples)

**Lab Sequence:**

#### Lab 1 — Thundering Herd
```
Scenario: Cache miss storm on cold start / cache eviction
Pattern:  singleflight + jitter on retry
Metrics:  cache_hit_ratio, origin_rps, p99_latency
```
Key Go primitives: `golang.org/x/sync/singleflight`, `time.Duration` jitter with `rand`

#### Lab 2 — Connection Pool Exhaustion
```
Scenario: Downstream DB saturates under traffic spike
Pattern:  Pool sizing math + timeout budgets + queue depth metrics
Metrics:  db_pool_wait_duration, db_pool_size, db_query_errors_total
```
Key Go primitives: `database/sql` MaxOpenConns/MaxIdleConns, `context.WithTimeout`

#### Lab 3 — Cascading Timeout Failure
```
Scenario: 50ms downstream p99 → 5s upstream collapse
Pattern:  Context deadline propagation, per-hop timeout budgets
Metrics:  request_duration_seconds (per service), deadline_exceeded_total
```
Key Go primitives: `context.WithDeadline`, deadline remaining check before each hop

#### Lab 4 — Goroutine Leak Detection
```
Scenario: Goroutines spawned without cancellation → OOM over hours
Pattern:  Leak detection via pprof, goroutine lifecycle ownership
Metrics:  go_goroutines (runtime metric), pprof goroutine profiles
```
Key Go primitives: `runtime/pprof`, `goleak` in tests, `context.Done()` select patterns

---

### 3. Production Code Audit Checklist

Use during PR reviews, design reviews, and incident retrospectives.

#### A. Timeout & Deadline Propagation
- [ ] Every outbound call (HTTP, DB, gRPC, cache) has an explicit timeout
- [ ] `context.Context` is the first parameter of every function in the call chain
- [ ] Deadline budget is checked before starting expensive work (`ctx.Err() != nil`)
- [ ] Per-hop timeouts sum to less than the top-level SLA

#### B. Error Handling at Service Boundaries
- [ ] Errors are wrapped with context (`fmt.Errorf("calling user-service: %w", err)`)
- [ ] Retries use exponential backoff with jitter — never bare retry loops
- [ ] Circuit breaker or bulkhead pattern on every critical downstream
- [ ] Distinction between retryable and non-retryable errors is explicit

#### C. Resource Lifecycle
- [ ] Every goroutine has a named owner and a clear exit condition
- [ ] `defer cancel()` immediately follows every `context.WithCancel/Timeout/Deadline`
- [ ] DB/HTTP connections are closed via `defer` or explicit lifecycle management
- [ ] File handles and network connections are audited for leak paths

#### D. Observability Hooks
- [ ] Request duration histogram at every service boundary (not just ingress)
- [ ] Error rate counter with error type label
- [ ] Resource saturation metric (pool size, queue depth, goroutine count)
- [ ] Runbook link in every alert rule

#### E. Graceful Degradation
- [ ] Every non-critical dependency has a defined fallback (cache, default, skip)
- [ ] Degraded mode is tested — not just happy path
- [ ] Load shedding strategy exists for sustained overload (queue depth limit, priority)
- [ ] Graceful shutdown drains in-flight requests before exit

---

### 4. Case Study Analysis Framework

For each case study (Knight Capital, AWS outages, etc.), apply:

```
1. TIMELINE     — What happened, in what order
2. TRIGGER      — The single event that started the cascade
3. AMPLIFIER    — What made it worse (missing circuit breaker, retry storm, etc.)
4. BLAST RADIUS — Actual user/revenue impact
5. DETECTION    — How long until someone knew (and why that long)
6. PATTERN      — Which failure mode category (thundering herd, split-brain, etc.)
7. TRANSFERABLE — What checklist item would have caught this
```

**Knight Capital (2012):**
- Trigger: Stale deploy flag activated old trading logic on 8 of 9 servers
- Amplifier: No kill switch, no automated position limit, no real-time P&L alert
- Pattern: Partial deploy + missing blast radius containment
- Transferable: Audit item — "Is partial rollout detectable and reversible within 60s?"

**AWS US-EAST-1 (various):**
- Common pattern: Control plane overload cascades to data plane
- Transferable: Audit item — "Does your service degrade if its own config/discovery system is slow?"

---

## Reasoning Templates

### Timeout Budget Calculation
```
Top-level SLA:     500ms p99
  └─ Auth service:  30ms (p99 budget)
  └─ User service:  80ms (p99 budget)
  └─ DB query:     100ms (p99 budget)
  └─ Business logic: 50ms
  └─ Buffer:       240ms (for GC, scheduling, serialization)

Rule: Each hop's timeout = its p99 budget × 1.5 (safety margin)
```

### Blast Radius Estimation Template
```
Failure at: [component]
Direct impact: [what calls this component]
Indirect impact: [what calls the callers]
User-facing symptoms: [what the user sees]
Revenue impact: [% of transactions affected × $/transaction]
Time to detect: [based on current alerting]
Time to mitigate: [manual vs automated]
```

---

## Go Patterns Quick Reference

| Problem | Pattern | Key API |
|---|---|---|
| Cache stampede | singleflight | `golang.org/x/sync/singleflight` |
| Downstream overload | Circuit breaker | `github.com/sony/gobreaker` |
| Retry storms | Backoff + jitter | `github.com/cenkalti/backoff/v4` |
| Goroutine leak | Context cancellation | `context.WithCancel` + `select` |
| Partial failure | Bulkhead | Separate worker pools per dependency |
| Timeout cascade | Deadline budget | `context.WithDeadline` + remaining check |
| Overload shedding | Token bucket | `golang.org/x/time/rate` |

---

## Output Defaults

When generating code labs:
- Include Prometheus metric registration and instrumentation
- Use `log/slog` for structured logging
- Add a `// FAILURE POINT:` comment at the line where the failure manifests
- Add a `// MITIGATION:` comment at the fix
- Include a `TestXxx_UnderLoad` benchmark test

When writing audit feedback:
- Quote the specific line of code
- Name the failure mode it enables
- Give the one-line fix
- Link to the relevant checklist item
